    en:
      'The Evidence-Informed Healthcare Renewal (EIHR) Portal is a continuously updated repository of policy-relevant documents that address ‘healthcare renewal’ in Canada. Healthcare renewal is defined as renewing, reforming or strengthening governance, financial and delivery arrangements within health systems (or, said another way, renewing, reforming or strengthening the health system arrangements that deliver cost-effective programs, services and drugs to those who need them). Documents within the EIHR Portal are contributed by <a href="http://www.cihr-irsc.gc.ca/e/44928.html" target="_blank">participating members</a> of the EIHR Roundtable.\n\n<p>Twenty-five types of policy-relevant documents are included in the EIHR Portal:</p>\n\n<ol>\n\n<li><b>Health and health system data</b> - Provides analyses of health (and health determinants) and health system data that provide the context for healthcare renewal;</li>\n\n<li><b>Health expenditure review</b> - Provides data on public spending in the health sector in comparison to other social sectors and against effectiveness, efficiency, equity and sustainability (and other healthcare renewal) parameters (adapted from Health Systems 20/20), either on its own or as the health chapter of national public expenditure reviews, and in a way that provides the context for healthcare renewal;</li>\n\n<li><b>National health account</b> - Provides information on the flow of all health funds from financing sources to end users in a health system (adapted from Health Systems 20/20) in a way that provides the context for healthcare renewal;</li>\n\n<li><b>Health system research priorities</b> - Describes research priorities for healthcare renewal for the jurisdiction;</li>\n\n<li><b>Situation analysis</b> - Describes an analysis of a current policy issue or domain related to healthcare renewal within a single jurisdiction;</li>\n\n<li><b>Jurisdictional review</b> - Describes what two or more jurisdictions are doing with respect to a policy issue or domain related to healthcare renewal;</li>\n\n<li><b>Performance review</b> - Describes the performance of one or more jurisdictions against explicit healthcare renewal objectives;</li>\n\n<li><b>External evaluation</b> - Describes the findings of an external evaluation of a large-scale healthcare renewal effort;</li>\n\n<li><b>Literature review</b> - Summarizes the research literature about healthcare renewal or a policy issue or domain related to healthcare renewal but doesn’t meet the criteria for a systematic review, which is a type of document already included in Health Systems Evidence;</li>\n\n<li><b>Framework</b> - Provides a framework that policymakers, stakeholders and researchers can use to undertake or monitor progress in healthcare renewal;</li>\n\n<li><b>Toolkit</b> - Provides tools that policymakers, stakeholders and researchers can use to undertake or monitor progress in healthcare renewal;</li>\n\n<li><b>Options framing</b> - Provides a summary to policymakers and stakeholders of what\'s known about options for how to undertake or monitor progress in healthcare renewal;</li>\n\n<li><b>Guidance</b> - Provides systematically developed recommendations to policymakers and stakeholders about how to undertake or monitor progress in healthcare renewal;</li>\n\n<li><b>Citizen/patient input</b> - Describes citizens’/patients’ views about and experiences with healthcare renewal or with a policy issue or domain related to healthcare renewal;</li>\n\n<li><b>Stakeholder input</b> - Describes stakeholders’ views about and experiences with healthcare renewal or with a policy issue or domain related to healthcare renewal;</li>\n\n<li><b>Stakeholder position paper</b> - Describes a stakeholder’s recommendations for or contributions to healthcare renewal;</li>\n\n<li><b>Government discussion paper</b> - Describes a government’s considerations related to healthcare renewal or a policy issue or domain related to healthcare renewal;</li>\n\n<li><b>Government position paper</b> - Describes a government’s plans for, or progress in, healthcare renewal (e.g., strategic plan related to healthcare renewal or annual reports related to healthcare renewal);</li>\n\n<li><b>Government strategic plan for the health sector</b> - Describes a government’s plan for the health system as a whole, including any statements about health system goals and health sector development programs, that provide the context for healthcare renewal;</li>\n\n<li><b>Government policy</b> - Describes a set of decisions or commitments to pursue courses of action aimed at achieving defined goals related to healthcare renewal (adapted from WHO EURO);</li>\n\n<li><b>Government legislation</b> - Articulates the law that provides the government authority to make regulations regarding healthcare renewal (adapted from Health Canada);</li>\n\n<li><b>Intergovernmental communiqué</b> - Describes a collective government statement related to healthcare renewal;</li>\n\n<li><b>Intergovernmental accord</b> - Describes a collective government commitment to healthcare renewal; and</li>\n\n<li><b>Government/third party accord</b> - Describes a joint commitment by a government and a third party (e.g., pharmaceutical or healthcare insurance company) to support healthcare renewal.</li>\n\n<li><b>Political party platform</b> – Describes a set of political party commitments related to healthcare renewal (and other topics) that would be implemented if the political party is elected to office.</li>\n\n</ol>\n\n<p>The documents address priority areas identified by Canadian federal, provincial and territorial governments such as primary healthcare, patient safety, health human resources, and performance indicators (e.g., timely access).</p>\n\n<p>The documents contributed by organizations participating in the EIHR Roundtable were deemed eligible for inclusion and coded by two independent reviewers if they address or could inform healthcare renewal in Canada and were one of 25 eligible document types. The details for these documents within Health Systems Evidence are provided in English and French.</p>\n\n<p>Each document contained in the EIHR Portal is described in terms of how recently the document was published and is linked to user-friendly summaries and full-text reports (if applicable and when freely available) as well as to any related documents already included in Health Systems Evidence (e.g., systematic reviews and economic evaluations in these priority areas).</p>',
